lass="clean-btn"><span class="copyButtonIcons_eSgA" aria-hidden="true"><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="copyButtonIcon_y97N"><path fill="currentColor" d="M19,21H8V7H19M19,5H8A2,2 0 0,0 6,7V21A2,2 0 0,0 8,23H19A2,2 0 0,0 21,21V7A2,2 0 0,0 19,5M16,1H4A2,2 0 0,0 2,3V17H4V3H16V1Z"></path></svg><svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" class="copyButtonSuccessIcon_LjdS"><path fill="currentColor" d="M21,7L9,19L3.5,13.5L4.91,12.09L9,16.17L19.59,5.59L21,7Z"></path></svg></span></button></div></div></div>
<h2 class="anchor anchorWithStickyNavbar_LWe7" id="conclusion">Conclusion<a href="https://eclipse.dev/lmos/blog/Spring.AI-integration#conclusion" class="hash-link" aria-label="Direct link to Conclusion" title="Direct link to Conclusion">​</a></h2>
<p>Using the new adapter for Spring.AI <code>SpringChatClient</code> can greatly reduce
the time of implementation for anyone who has used Spring.AI before.
By following the before mentioned steps, you can integrate any of the
Spring.AI models that cater to the specific needs of your applications.</p>
<p>Remember to choose an AI service that aligns with your project's goals and
requirements, and don't hesitate to reach out if you have any questions or
need further guidance on implementing a ARC agent. Happy coding!</p>
